'''Amanda Cameron Flower''' (sometimes '''Flowers''') (October 15, 1863 - November 20, 1940) was an [[United States|American]] [[Spiritualism|Spiritualist]] pastor and [[spirit medium]] of [[Canada|Canadian]] birth.
Flower was a native of [[Owen Sound]], [[Ontario]], who came to the United States at the age of 27.<ref name="encyclopedia.com">{{cite web|url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/science/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/flower-amanda-cameron-1863-1940|title=Flower, Amanda Cameron (1863-1940) - Encyclopedia.com|website=www.encyclopedia.com|accessdate=23 August 2018}}</ref> She settled in [[Michigan]], where she purchased a church building in [[Grand Rapids, Michigan|Grand Rapids]], which she proceeded to reopen as the First Church of Truth. She served as its pastor from 1904 until 1939. She began to open other Spiritualist churches across the [[Midwestern United States]], all affiliated with the [[National Spiritualist Association of Churches]], but she became irritated at their rules about ministers and in 1924 she founded the [[Independent Spiritualist Association]],<ref name="LindleyStebner2008">{{cite book|author1=Susan Hill Lindley|author2=Eleanor J. Stebner|title=The Westminster Handbook to Women in American Religious History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R4hLAtDBHskC&pg=PA134|year=2008|publisher=Westminster John Knox Press|isbn=978-0-664-22454-7|page=79}}</ref> having in the meantime incorporated some elements of [[Theosophy (Blavatskian)|theosophy]], including a belief in [[reincarnation]], into her spirituality.<ref name="encyclopedia.com"/> She established their newsletter, editing it until 1935, and in 1931 she was elected president-for-life of the group. Her name is given inconsistently in the Association's materials, sometimes as "Flower" and sometimes as "Flowers".<ref name="LindleyStebner2008"/>
