{{Infobox criminal | name = Bernardo Bandini Baroncelli | image = Leonardo da Vinci - Hanging of Bernardo Baroncelli 1479.jpg | caption = Hanging of Bernardo Baroncelli in Florence by [[Leonardo da Vinci]] | birth_name = Bernardo Bandini dei Baroncelli | birth_date = January 15, 1420 | birth_place = [[Florence]], [[Italy]] | death_date = {{death date and age|1479|12|29|1420|01|15}} | death_place = Florence, Italy | death_cause = [[Death by hanging|Hanging]] | occupation = [[Merchant]] | victims = [[Giuliano de' Medici]] | date = 26 April 1478 | country = Italy | locations = [[Duomo of Florence]] | targets = [[Medici]] | fatalities = Giuliano de' Medici | injuries = [[Lorenzo de' Medici]] | weapons = [[Knife]] }}
'''Bernardo Bandini Baroncelli''' (15 January 1420 – 29 December 1479) was an Italian [[merchant]] and one of the instigators of the [[Pazzi Conspiracy]].<ref>{{DBI |title=BANDINI dei Baroncelli, Bernardo |url=http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/bandini-dei-baroncelli-bernardo_(Dizionario-Biografico)/ |last=Pampaloni |first=Guido |volume=5 }}</ref>
As the opening stroke of the Pazzi Conspiracy, [[Giuliano de' Medici]] was assassinated on [[Easter Sunday]], 26 April 1478 in the [[Duomo of Florence]], [[Santa Maria del Fiore]], by [[Francesco de' Pazzi]] and Bernardo Baroncelli.<ref>{{cite book |last=Smedley |first=Edward |last2=James |first2=Hugh James |last3=Rose |first3=Henry John |title=Encyclopaedia Metropolitana; Or, Universal Dictionary of Knowledge on an Original Plan Comprising the Twofold Advantage of a Philosophical and an Alphabetical Arrangement, with Appropriate Engravings |url=https://archive.org/stream/bub_gb_QGM8I7n97nEC#page/n279 |publisher=B. Fellowes |page=272 |year=1845}}</ref> Giuliano was killed by a sword wound to the head and was stabbed 19 times.<ref>{{cite book |first=Rachel A. |last=Koestler-Grack |title=Leonardo Da Vinci: Artist, Inventor, and Renaissance Man |url=https://books.google.es/books?id=6wyF_sEAwLUC&printsec=frontcover |editor-first=Michael |editor-last=Joseph |year=1974 |publisher=[[Infobase Publishing]] |pages=152 |isbn=978-0791086261}}</ref> Baroncelli was arrested in [[Constantinopole]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ru/books?id=PPxC6rO7vvsC&pg=PA385&lpg=PA385&dq=giuliano+medici+murderer+istanbul&source=bl&ots=ISu4jpiHeq&sig=WlYRuL_VWDXSapYWGSbfvMzlQZY&hl=ru&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjBwfu9u5LdAhVIkCwKHe4CC20Q6AEwCXoECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=giuliano%20medici%20murderer%20istanbul&f=false|title=Mehmed the Conqueror and His Time|last=Babinger|first=Franz|date=1992|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=0691010781|language=en}}</ref> Antonio Medici was sent to deliver him from Istanbul. Bandini was hanged on 29 December at the [[Palazzo del Bargello]].<ref>{{cite book |first=Giovanni di Jacopo |last=Morelli |first2=Lionardo di Lorenzo |last2=Morelli |last3=di San Luigi |first3=Idelfonso |title=Croniche |location=Firenze |publisher=Gaetano Cambiagi |year=1785 |url=https://books.google.it/books?id=boYHAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA195 |page=195}}</ref>
Bernardo Baroncelli was drawn in a macabre sketch by [[Leonardo da Vinci]] in Florence in 1479 showing the body of Bernardo Baroncelli hanged, in connection with the murder of Giuliano in the [[Pazzi conspiracy]].<ref>{{cite book |first=A. E. |last=Popham |title=The Drawings of Leonardo da Vinci |year=1946 |url=https://books.google.es/books?id=oVelswEACAAJ |pages=184}}</ref> With dispassionate integrity Leonardo has registered in neat [[mirror writing]] the colours of the robes that Baroncelli was wearing when he died.
==In popular culture== Bernardo Baroncelli is played by Giovanni Pagliano as a [[tenor voice]] in the opera ''[[I Medici]]'', composed by [[Ruggero Leoncavallo]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://amadeusonline.eu/almanacco.php?Start=0&Giorno=9&Mese=11&Anno=1893&Giornata=&Testo=&Parola=Stringa |title=Almanacco 9 November 1893 |publisher=AmadeusOnline |language=it |access-date=30 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.musicweb-international.com/classrev/2010/Aug10/leoncavallo_4777456.htm |title=Review - Leoncavallo - I Medici |first=Robert J. |last=Farr |date=August 2010 |publisher=MusicWeb International |access-date=30 August 2010}}</ref> He appears in the videogame ''[[Assassin's Creed II]]'' and is killed by [[Ezio Auditore]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/assassins-creed-ii-walkthrough/1100-6242715/ |title=Assassin's Creed II Walkthrough |last=Segers |first=Andre |date=3 February 2012 |access-date=10 May 2018 |work=[[GameSpot]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive Inc.]]}}</ref>
